On the evening of 23 August 2024, a mass stabbing took place during a festival celebrating the 650th anniversary of Solingen, Germany, when a Syrian man armed with a knife killed three people and injured eight others.
The motive for the attack, according to authorities, were the suspect's "radical Islamist convictions".[1][2] The suspect is believed to be a member of Islamic State, which has claimed responsibility for the attack.
Prior to the stabbing, a rise in knife attacks in Germany, particularly in city centers and at railway stations, had prompted interior minister Nancy Faeser earlier in August 2024 to call for more stringent restrictions on knives in public places, with exceptions only for household knives in closed packaging that have just been bought.
The Nanjing Massacre[1] or the Rape of Nanjing (formerly romanized as Nanking[note 2]) was the mass murder of Chinese civilians in Nanjing, the capital of the Republic of China, immediately after the Battle of Nanking and the retreat of the National Revolutionary Army in the Second Sino-Japanese War, by the Imperial Japanese Army.[2][3][4][5] Beginning on December 13, 1937, the massacre lasted six weeks.[note 1] The perpetrators also committed other war crimes such as mass rape, looting, torture, and arson.
The massacre is considered to be one of the worst wartime atrocities.[7][8][9]
Rape and looting was widespread.
Due to multiple factors, death toll estimates vary from 40,000 to over 300,000, with rape cases ranging from 20,000 to over 80,000 cases.
In addition, Jiading was shelled by Japanese forces, then 8,000 of its civilian residents indiscriminately murdered.
Chinese civilians often committed suicide, such as two girls who deliberately drowned themselves near Pinghu, an event witnessed by Japanese First Lieutenant Nishizawa Benkichi.
